{"title_page": "Thouqan Hindawi", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox Prime Minister\n|name=Thuqan Hindawi\n|office2=President of the Royal Hashemite Court\n|image=Thouqan_Hindawi.jpg\n|termstart1=1993\n|termstart2=1989\n|office1=Deputy Prime Minister of Jordan\n|resting_place=The Royal Tombs of the Hashemite, Al-Maquar\n|honorific-prefix=[[Excellency|His Excellency]]\n|birth_date={{birth date|1927|6|23}}\n|death_date={{death date and age|2005|7|2|1927|6|23}}\n|death_place=[[Amman, Jordan]]\n|parents=Salem Hindawi {{small|(father)}}\n|termend2=1995\n|termend1=1995\n|nationality=[[Jordan]]ian\n|monarch1=[[King Hussein]]|monarch2=[[King Hussein]]|country1=Jordan|primeminister1=[[Abdelsalam al-Majali]]|primeminister2=[[Mudar Badran]]\n[[Zaid ibn Shaker]]|birth_place=[[Irbid, Jordan]]|birth_name=Thouqan Hindawi}}\n\n'''Thuqan Hindawi''' was born in 1927 in the Hindawi Madafa of his father Sheikh Salem Basha Hindawi in the northern part of the Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan which was the [[Emirate of Transjordan]] at that time. During his life, Hindawi served in several key government positions for over 40 years from 1965 until 2005. Some of these positions include but not limited to Chief of [[The Royal Hashemite Court|Royal Hashemite Court]], Deputy Prime Minister, Minister of Education, Minister of Finance, Senator, and Ambassador. \n\n== Education ==\nThouqan Hindawi studied at the [[Arab College (Jerusalem)|Arab College]] in Jerusalem, and later received a [[Bachelor of Arts|Bachelor's]] degree in English from the [[University of London]], a [[Bachelor of Arts|Bachelor's]] degree in History from [[Cairo University]] and a [[Master's degree]] in Advanced Education from the [[University of Maryland]].<ref>https://archive.org/stream/JordanTimes1991JordanEnglish/Nov%2023%201991%2C%20Jordan%20Times%2C%20%234862%2C%20Jordan%20%28en%29_djvu.txt</ref>\n\n== Occupation ==\n\nHindawi began his career working at Karak High School, and later moved to the School of [[Irb\nid]]. He served as an Inspector at the Ministry of Education between 1950-1955, and as the Director of Teacher Training in Beit Hanina of [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]] between 1955-1960.\n\n[[File:Thouqan with king.jpg|left|thumb|Hussein of Jordan & Thouqan\n]]\n\nIn 1962, Hindawi became the Director General of the Department of Social Affairs and Relief Agency ([[UNRWA|United Nations Relief and Works Agency]]),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unrwa.org/|title=UNRWA {{!}} United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees in the Near East|website=UNRWA|access-date=2016-04-05}}</ref> and an inspector in the [[Ministry_of_Education_(Egypt)|Ministry of Education]]. He returned in 1964 and was recognized at the Jordanian Embassy in Cairo,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.embassypages.com/missions/embassy17161/|title=Embassy of Jordan in Cairo, Egypt|website=www.embassypages.com|access-date=2016-04-05}}</ref> He then took the first ministerial post in 1965, as Minister of the Media with then Prime Minister [[Wasfi al-Tal]].\n\nFrom 1965 to 1995, Hindawi held several ministerial positions, including the [[Minister of Education]] from 1965-1970, [[Deputy Prime Minister]] from 1993-1995, [[Minister of State]], [[Chairman]] of [[The Royal Hashemite Court]],<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal |title=The Royal Hashemite Court |url=http://www.rhc.jo |journal=Main Website |language=en}}</ref> Ambassador of Jordan<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jordanembassy.org.au/|title=Home|website=www.jordanembassy.org.au|access-date=2016-04-05}}</ref>, Ambassador to Kuwait<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.embassypages.com/missions/embassy17523/|title=Embassy of Jordan in Kuwait City, Kuwait|website=www.embassypages.com|access-date=2016-04-05}}</ref> and Deputy elected by the people. From 1995-2004 Hindawi was appointed as a member of the Notables Council and Senior Vice President and the head of a number of committees, including the Foreign Education.\n\nHe was a member of the Board of Trustees of the [[University of Jordan]], [[Yarmouk University]], and Chairman of the Board of Trustees of the Arab Community College. He received several prestigious international awards from a variety of countries and institutions.\n\n\n\n== Death  ==\nHindawi died on July 2, 2005, and was buried in the Royal Tombs of the Hashemite<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unofficialroyalty.com/royal-burial-sites/jordanian-royal-burial-sites/|title=Jordanian Royal Burial Sites|website=Unofficial Royalty|language=en-US|access-date=2016-04-05}}</ref> near the tomb of [[Hussein of Jordan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kinghussein.gov.jo/biography.html|title=Biography - His Majesty King Hussein bin Talal|website=www.kinghussein.gov.jo|access-date=2016-04-05}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* http://www.pm.gov.jo/arabic/index.php?page_type=news&part=1&id=890\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hindawi, Thouqan}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2005 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox Prime Minister\n|name=Thuqan Hindawi\n|office2=President of the Royal Hashemite Court\n|image=Thouqan_Hindawi.jpg\n|termstart1=1993\n|termstart2=1989\n|office1=Deputy Prime Minister of Jordan\n|resting_place=The Royal Tombs of the Hashemite, Al-Maquar\n|honorific-prefix=[[Excellency|His Excellency]]\n|birth_date={{birth date|1927|6|23}}\n|death_date={{death date and age|2005|7|2|1927|6|23}}\n|death_place=[[Amman, Jordan]]\n|parents=Salem Hindawi {{small|(father)}}\n|termend2=1995\n|termend1=1995\n|nationality=[[Jordan]]ian\n|monarch1=[[King Hussein]]|monarch2=[[King Hussein]]|country1=Jordan|primeminister1=[[Abdelsalam al-Majali]]|primeminister2=[[Mudar Badran]]\n[[Zaid ibn Shaker]]|birth_place=[[Irbid, Jordan]]|birth_name=Thouqan Hindawi}}\n\n'''Thuqan Hindawi''' was born in 1927 in the Hindawi Madafa of his father Sheikh Salem Basha Hindawi in the northern part of the Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan which was the [[Emirate of Transjordan]] at that time. During his life Hindawi served in several key government positions for over 40 years from 1965 until 2005. Some of these positions include but not limited to Chief of [[The Royal Hashemite Court|Royal Hashemite Court]], Deputy Prime Minister, Minister of Education, Minister of Finance, Senator, and Ambassador. \n\n== Education ==\nThouqan Hindawi studied at the [[Arab College (Jerusalem)|Arab College]] in Jerusalem, and later received a [[Bachelor of Arts|Bachelor's]] degree in English from the [[University of London]], a [[Bachelor of Arts|Bachelor's]] degree in History from [[Cairo University]] and a [[Master's degree]] in Advanced Education from the [[University of Maryland]].<ref>https://archive.org/stream/JordanTimes1991JordanEnglish/Nov%2023%201991%2C%20Jordan%20Times%2C%20%234862%2C%20Jordan%20%28en%29_djvu.txt</ref>\n\n== Occupation ==\n\nHindawi began his career working at Karak High School, and later moved to the School of [[Irb\nid]]. He served as an Inspector at the Ministry of Education between 1950-1955, and as the Director of Teacher Training in Beit Hanina of [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]] between 1955-1960.\n\n[[File:Thouqan with king.jpg|left|thumb|Hussein of Jordan & Thouqan\n]]\n\nIn 1962, Hindawi became the Director General of the Department of Social Affairs and Relief Agency ([[UNRWA|United Nations Relief and Works Agency]]),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unrwa.org/|title=UNRWA {{!}} United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees in the Near East|website=UNRWA|access-date=2016-04-05}}</ref> and an inspector in the [[Ministry_of_Education_(Egypt)|Ministry of Education]]. He returned in 1964 and was recognized at the Jordanian Embassy in Cairo,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.embassypages.com/missions/embassy17161/|title=Embassy of Jordan in Cairo, Egypt|website=www.embassypages.com|access-date=2016-04-05}}</ref> He then took the first ministerial post in 1965, as Minister of the Media with then Prime Minister [[Wasfi al-Tal]].\n\nFrom 1965 to 1995, Hindawi held several ministerial positions, including the [[Minister of Education]] from 1965-1970, [[Deputy Prime Minister]] from 1993-1995, [[Minister of State]], [[Chairman]] of [[The Royal Hashemite Court]],<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal |title=The Royal Hashemite Court |url=http://www.rhc.jo |journal=Main Website |language=en}}</ref> Ambassador of Jordan<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jordanembassy.org.au/|title=Home|website=www.jordanembassy.org.au|access-date=2016-04-05}}</ref>, Ambassador to Kuwait<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.embassypages.com/missions/embassy17523/|title=Embassy of Jordan in Kuwait City, Kuwait|website=www.embassypages.com|access-date=2016-04-05}}</ref> and Deputy elected by the people. From 1995-2004 Hindawi was appointed as a member of the Notables Council and Senior Vice President and the head of a number of committees, including the Foreign Education.\n\nHe was a member of the Board of Trustees of the [[University of Jordan]], [[Yarmouk University]], and Chairman of the Board of Trustees of the Arab Community College. He received several prestigious international awards from a variety of countries and institutions.\n\n\n\n== Death  ==\nHindawi died on July 2, 2005, and was buried in the Royal Tombs of the Hashemite<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unofficialroyalty.com/royal-burial-sites/jordanian-royal-burial-sites/|title=Jordanian Royal Burial Sites|website=Unofficial Royalty|language=en-US|access-date=2016-04-05}}</ref> near the tomb of [[Hussein of Jordan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kinghussein.gov.jo/biography.html|title=Biography - His Majesty King Hussein bin Talal|website=www.kinghussein.gov.jo|access-date=2016-04-05}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* http://www.pm.gov.jo/arabic/index.php?page_type=news&part=1&id=890\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hindawi, Thouqan}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2005 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "The History A